  "opinion": "As a 44-year-old plumber living in Los Angeles, I've seen firsthand how fake content on social media can cause real problems, and I believe managing it requires a practical, hands-on approach. I spend about an hour daily on social media, mostly to unwind after a long day of fixing pipes and drains, and I use it to share photos from my hobbies like birdwatching and photography or to catch up on news and entertainment. Being an immigrant and a Muslim, I value truth and community, so when I come across fake posts—whether they're misleading news stories or doctored images—it really bothers me. My high conscientiousness score means I'm detail-oriented and responsible, so I take the time to check sources before sharing anything. For example, if I see a viral claim about a local issue in LA, I'll look up reliable news sites or ask trusted friends rather than just passing it along. My low openness score makes me cautious about new or sensational information, so I stick to what I know is credible. I think social media platforms should do more to flag or remove fake content, but as users, we also have a role to play. I teach my friends and family to be skeptical and to verify facts, especially since fake content can spread fear or division, which goes against my religious beliefs in peace and honesty. My high neuroticism means I get anxious about misinformation, so I limit my exposure by following only accounts I trust and avoiding heated debates online. In my work as a plumber, I rely on accuracy and trust—if I give bad advice, it could lead to costly damages—and I apply that same mindset to social media. By being curious but careful, we can all help reduce the impact of fake content and keep our online spaces more truthful and supportive.",
